Area of a fish pass for the fish to pass waterway dams or weirs. Should contain waterway=fish_pass way inside.
A natural or semi-natural body of relatively still fresh or salt water which is surrounded by land
An artificial lake which may be used to store water.
A small body of standing water, man-made in most cases
An area of land artificially graded to hold water.
A lagoon: a body of shallow sea water or brackish water separated from the sea by a barrier.
A stream pool: a small but relatively deep collection of fresh water, occurring along a narrow stream
A reflecting pool: a water feature found in gardens, squares, and at memorial sites, which consists of a shallow pool of water, undisturbed by fountain jets, for a calm reflective surface.
A deep, wide defensive ditch, normally filled with water, dug to surround a fortified habitation.
A clarifier/settling basin of a wastewater treatment plant.
The linear flow of a river, in flow direction.
The water-covered area of a river
A naturally-forming waterway that is too narrow to be classed as a river.
A natural intertidal waterway in mangroves, salt marshes and tidal flats with water flow in the direction of the tide
An artificial '''open flow''' waterway used to carry useful water for transportation, waterpower, or irrigation.
An artificial free flow waterway used for carrying superfluous water, usually lined with concrete.
A small man-made drainage waterway, usually unlined.
An artificial waterway where water flows in a closed space without air
A navigable route in a lake or sea, often marked by buoys or beacons.
An enclosed area of water for ships and other craft within which the height of the water can be managed.
A place for constructing, repairing and storing vessels out of the water.
A barrier built across a river or stream to block and regulate the flow of the river.
A barrier built across a river to control water speed and depth. Designed to let water flow over the top all the time or at least in specific conditions.
A place where water flows over a vertical drop or a series of drops in the course of a stream or river.
A gate of a lock
The point at which a river or stream percolates into or through the soil
A place to turn the driving direction for vessels, where the boats are longer than the river/canal is wide.
A place to fill fresh water holding tanks of a boat.
A place to get fuel for boats
Means a feature that is normally linear is an area. You should not add this to features that are already defined as an area type.

Description: A bridge, use together with the tag layer=*. Value /yes/ is generic, or you can specialize.
Used for specifying how much is charged for use/access to a facility. See toll=* or fee=*.
Used to denote that a node, way or area is covered by another entity (or in some cases the ground), when the use of layers is inappropriate, or additional clarification is needed.

Specifies whether a pedestrian crossing has a refuge island
A cut in the land to carry a road or tram. Mostly in hilly landscape. See Cutting on Wikipedia
For features that are useful for navigation, yet are unused. See abandoned=* if infrastructure is removed.
Used to indicate if a pharmacy, bank, atm, or fast_food, or post_box offers drive_thru service. drive_through=* is different than drive_in=*}
Used to indicate if a cinema is a drive-in cinema or a restaurant offers drive-in service. drive_in=* is different than drive_through=*
Indicates infrastructure to supply vehicles with electricity on rail tracks
Elevation (also known as altitude or height) above mean sea level in metre, based on geoid model EGM 96 which is used by WGS 84 (GPS). (see also Altitude)

Access permission for Wikipedia-16px Road Train B-double. A B-double (B-Train) consists of a prime mover towing a specialised trailer (known as a "lead" or "A"-trailer) that has a fifth-wheel mounted on the rear towing another semi-trailer, resulting in two articulation points.

Access permission for bicycles. Usage of bicycle=dismount and bicycle=no will vary in different countries. If according to local traffic rules a bicycle is no longer seen as a bicycle when there's no one driving it, then there's no need for using bicycle=dismount. If the local legislation still sees an undriven bicycle as a bicycle then you may need to use both bicycle=dismount and bicycle=no.
